{"attack":true,"case":"The target's central sufficiency claim is self-contradicted by its own forbidden case and scope, violating std-crit-design clause (1). The claim asserts a strict biconditional: harness strictly beats SC *iff* (A) question-conditional net signal is positive AND (B) majority is fragile. The scope then covers 'regimes where critic positive-class precision exceeds 0.5 on fragile-majority questions' and 'critic confidence and correctness are positively correlated on fragile questions' — i.e., both (A) and (B) are asserted to hold. Yet the target's own second forbidden case specifies: at P(fragile)=0.2 (satisfying B) with critic precision-on-fragile=0.7 (satisfying A and the scope threshold), harness < SC by >=0.05, which the target itself says would refute 'the sufficiency of the proposed condition.' So the proposal simultaneously (a) claims sufficiency, (b) scopes to the regime where the sufficient conditions hold, and (c) pre-registers a measurable outcome inside that same regime that refutes sufficiency. A proposal that pre-registers its own refutation inside its claimed-sufficient regime does not 'name the specific mechanism or regime condition under which criticism-filtered voting diverges' — it names a condition, then concedes the condition is not sufficient. This is not an aspirational wording problem; it is a logical defect in the design: the sufficient condition is stated, scoped, and forbidden all at once. Clause (1) requires the proposal to state the regime under which divergence occurs in measurable quantities; the target instead states a regime, covers it, and then forbids the outcome where divergence goes the wrong way, which is exactly the false-flag-erosion failure the claim said could not happen under its conditions.","counterexample":null}